    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c47584f4c7bb9f54",
      "text": "Calibrating Noise to Sensitivity in Private Data Analysis is a paper by Cynthia Dwork, Frank McSherry, Kobbi Nissim, and Adam Smith that was published in the Journal of Privacy and Confidentiality in 2006. The paper presents a technique for protecting the privacy of individuals whose data is used to train a machine learning model. The technique is based on the idea of adding noise to the data in a way that is proportional to the \"sensitivity\" of the query being made. The sensitivity of a query is a measure of how much the query's output would change if the input data were slightly different.\n\nThe authors propose a framework for determining the appropriate amount of noise to add to the data based on the sensitivity of the query. They show that this technique can be used to provide \"differential privacy\" for the individuals whose data is being used, while still allowing the machine learning model to be trained on the data.\n\nIn summary, the paper presents a technique for preserving the privacy of individuals whose data is used to train a machine learning model by adding noise to the data in a way that is proportional to the sensitivity of the query being made, providing a framework for determining the appropriate amount of noise to add to the data and showing that this technique can be used to provide \"differential privacy\" for the individuals whose data is being used, while still allowing the machine learning model to be trained on the data."
