        "text": "The paper \"Calibrating Noise to Sensitivity in Private Data Analysis\" by Dwork, McSherry, Nissim and Smith defines privacy, or differential privacy, as a measure of the amount of information revealed about a single individual in a dataset when that individual's data is included or excluded from the dataset. The paper introduces a new measure of privacy loss called \"sensitivity\" which is defined as the maximum amount of change in the output of a query function when a single individual's data is included or excluded from the dataset. They propose to add noise to the query function's output to protect privacy, and the amount of noise added is calibrated to the sensitivity of the query function to protect the privacy of individuals. The paper also presents a mathematical proof of the privacy guarantees provided by this method, and it provides a formal definition of differential privacy. They also discuss how to balance privacy and utility by choosing the appropriate level of noise to add to the query function's output."
